<section id="title-slide">
<h1>Propositional logic 1</h1>
<h2>Defining the language</h2>

<p>Erik Hoversten</p>
<p>Rutgers university: LRP, fall 2014</p>
<p>October 22, 2014</p>

</section>

<section>
	<section>
	
<h2>A formal logic is defined by its language</h2>
<p>The key parts of any language are:</p>
<ul>
<li class="fragment">Vocabulary
<ul>
<li class="fragment">Logical vocabulary</li>
<li class="fragment">Non-logical vocabulary</li>
</ul></li>
<li class="fragment">Syntax
<ul>
<li class="fragment">Rules for putting vocabulary together into propositions</li>
</ul></li>
<li class="fragment">Semantics
<ul>
<li class="fragment">Rules for interpreting the meaning of propositions</li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
	</section>
	
	<section>
<h2 id="categorical-logic">Categorical logic</h2>
<p>In categorical logic, our language was:</p>
<ul>
<li class="fragment">Vocabulary
<ul>
<li class="fragment">Logical: Quantifiers and copula</li>
<li class="fragment">Non-logical: Subject and predicate terms</li>
</ul></li>
<li class="fragment">Syntax
<ul>
<li class="fragment">[Quantifier] + [Subject term] + [copula] + [Predicate term]</li>
</ul></li>
<li class="fragment">Semantics
<ul>
<li class="fragment">Specification of each proposition's meaning in terms of set <em>inclusion</em> and <em>exclusion</em></li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
	</section>

	<section>
<h2 id="propositional-logic">Propositional logic</h2>
<p>Propositional logic is another formal logic with a slightly different language:</p>
<ul>
<li class="fragment">Vocabulary
<ul>
<li class="fragment">Logical: 1-place connectives, 2-place connectives</li>
<li class="fragment">Non-logical: Propositions</li>
</ul></li>
<li class="fragment">Syntax
<ul>
<li class="fragment">[1-place connective] + [proposition]</li>
<li class="fragment">[proposition] + [2-place connective] + [propostition]</li>
</ul></li>
<li class="fragment">Semantics
<ul>
<li class="fragment">Meaning is specified in terms of <strong>truth conditions</strong></li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
	</section>
</section>

<section>
	<section>
<h1>Propositional logic</h1>
<p>We define the formal logic by specifying completely each component of the language used to express the logic</p>
	</section>

	<section>
<h2 id="vocabulary">Vocabulary</h2>
<p>Logical</p>

<ul>
<li class="fragment">1-place connective: </li>
<ul>
<li class="fragment">takes 1 proposition and makes a compound proposition</li>
<ul>
<li class="fragment"><strong>~ </strong> (tilde) :  <em>not</em>, <em>it is not the case that</em></li>
</ul></ul>
<li class="fragment">2-place connective: </li>
<ul>
<li class="fragment">take 2 propositions an make a compound proposition</li>
<ul>
<li class="fragment"><strong>&#x2219; </strong> (dot) :  <em>and</em>,  <em>in addition</em>, <em>both ... and ___ </em></li>
<li class="fragment"><strong>&#x2228; </strong> (vee) :  <em>or</em>,  <em>either ... or ___</em></li>
<li class="fragment"><strong>&#x2283; </strong> (horseshoe) :  <em>if ... then ___ </em>,  <em>... only if ___</em>,  <em>... unless ___</em></li>
<li class="fragment"><strong>&#x2261; </strong> (triple bar) : <em>... is equivalent to ___ </em>, <em>... if and only if ___</em></li>
</ul></ul>
<li class="fragment">Parentheses: <strong>( </strong>, <strong>) </strong></li>
</ul>
	</section>
	
	<section>
<h2 id="vocabulary">Vocabulary</h2>
<p>Non-logical</p>

<ul>
<li class="fragment">Atomic propositions:</li>
<ul><li class="fragment"> <em>John went to the store</em></li>
	<li class="fragment"><em>Mary ate baked tofu</em></li>
</ul>
<li class="fragment">We abstract over the content of propositions by replacing them with propositional variables:</li>
<ul><li class="fragment"><em>A, B, C, ...</em></li>
</ul>
</ul>
	</section>

	<section>
<h2 id="syntax">Syntax</h2>
<p>The sentences of propositional logic</p>
<ul>
<li class="fragment">[proposition]
<ul>
<li class="fragment"><strong>A</strong>, <strong>B</strong>, <strong>C</strong>, ...</li>
</ul></li>
<li class="fragment">[1-place connective] + [proposition]
<ul>
<li class="fragment">Negation: <strong>~A</strong></li>
</ul></li>
<li class="fragment">[proposition] + [2-place connective] + [proposition]
<ul>
<li class="fragment">Conjunction: <strong>A &#x2219; B</strong></li>
<li class="fragment">Disjunction: <strong>C &#x2228; D</strong></li>
<li class="fragment">Conditional: <strong>E &#x2283; F</strong></li>
<li class="fragment">Biconditional: <strong>G &#x2261; H</strong></li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
	</section>

	<section>
<h2 id="formulas">Formulas</h2>
<p>A <em>formula</em> is any combination of bits from the vocabulary of the language.</p>
<ul>
<li class="fragment">WFFs</li>
<ul>
<li class="fragment">Not all possible formulas belong to the language of propositional logic. The good ones must follow the syntax on the previous slide.</li>
<li class="fragment">Any syntactic unit that meets the specification above is a <strong>well-formed formula</strong> (<em>WFF</em>)</li>
<li class="fragment">The WFFs compose the entire language of propositional logic</li>
<li class="fragment">Propositional variables can stand for <em>any</em> WFF, either atomic or compound</li>
</ul></ul>
</section>

<section>
<h2 id="formulas">Recursion</h2>
<p>Compound propositions are also propositions, so we can use connectives to connect compound propositions as well as atomic ones.</p>
<ul>
<<<<<<< HEAD
<li class="fragment">The process of building bigger peices from smaller peices of the same type is known as <em>recursion</em></li>
<li class="fragment">We use parentheses to set off each compound proposition from the others in the WFF</li>
<li class="fragment">Examples:</li>
<ul> 
<li class="fragment"><em>(A &#x2219; B) &#x2283; (C &#x2228; D)</em></li>
<li class="fragment"><em>(~M &#x2261; Q) &#x2219; R</em></li>
=======
<li class="fragment">When we do, we surround each compound proposition with parentheses</li>
<li class="fragment">This is known as recursion*</li>
<li class="fragment">Examples:</li>
<ul> 
<li class="fragment"><em>(A &#x2219; B) &#x2283; (C &#x2228; D)</em>, <em>(~M &#x2261; Q) &#x2219; R</em></li>
>>>>>>> 5d886e5ff439688061ec66cc11bdf07adf23ca19
</ul>
</ul>

<p class="fragment">Languages with recursion are capable of expressing and <em>infinite</em> number of propositions.</p>
	</section>

	<section>
<h2 id="semantics">Semantics</h2>
<p>In propositional logic, we specify the meaning of WFFs in terms their <strong>truth conditions</strong>.</p>

<ul>
<li class="fragment">Truth conditions specify the <strong>way the world must be</strong> in order for the proposition to be true.</li>
<ul>
<li class="fragment">What a proposition <em>means</em> is the set of situations in which it is true.</li>
</ul>
<li class="fragment">Examples:</li>
<ul>
<li class="fragment"><em>Jack went to the store</em> is true <strong>just in case</strong> Jack went to the store.</li>
<li class="fragment"><em>Felicity got a perm and Mike likes it</em> is true <strong>just in case</strong> <em>both</em> Felicity got a perm <em>and</em> Mike likes Felicity's perm</li>
<li class="fragment"><em>Garth is at the party or he had a fight with Wayne</em> is true <strong>just in case</strong> <em>either</em> Garth is at the party <em>or</em> Garth had a fight with Wayne</li>
</ul>
</ul>
	</section>
</section>

<section>
	<section>
<h1>Truth tables</h1>
<p>In order to provide the meaning for a WFF, we need to outline the different <em>ways</em> it can be true or false. We do this by constructing a <strong>truth table</strong> for the WFF.</p>
<ul>
<li class="fragment">Atomic propositions can only be either true or false, so their truth table is pretty boring.</li>
<ul>
<li class="fragment">We list <strong>one row</strong> for each <em>distinct</em> way that the WFF might turn out. For atomic propositions, there are two distinct ways, thus two rows appear on the table.</li>
<li class="fragment">We put a <em>T</em> to stand for true and an <em>F</em> to stand for false</li>
</ul></ul>

<table>
<thead>
<th style="text-align: center;">A</th>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr class="odd">
<td style="text-align: center;">T</td>
</tr>
<tr class="even">
<td style="text-align: center;">F</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
<caption>Truth table for atomic propositions</caption>
</table>
	</section>

	<section>
<h2 id="truth-tables-for-compound-propositions">Truth tables for compound propositions</h2>
<p>Compound propositions have more <em>moving parts</em> than atomic ones, so their truth tables are more interesting.</p>
<p>To construct a truth table for a compound proposition we:</p>
<ol type="1">
<li>Make a <em>column</em> for every distinct propositional variable in the WFF</li>
<li>Add a column for the complete WFF</li>
<li>Make a <em>row</em> for every distinct combination of truth values those variables can have</li>
<ul>
<li>As a rule, if there are <em>n</em> propositional variables in the WFF, there will be <em>2<sup>n</sup></em> combinations of truth values</li>
<li>If the WFF includes an <em>A</em> and a <em>B</em>, there will be <strong>2<sup>2</sup> = 4</strong> rows in the table</li>
<li>If the WFF includes a <em>C</em>, a <em>D</em>, and an <em>E</em>, there will be <strong>2<sup>3</sup> = 8</strong> rows in the table</li>
</ul>
</ol>
</section>

<section>
<h2>Truth tables for compound propositions</h2>
<p>Filling the columns</p>

<ol type="1">
<li>Divide the number of rows in half. In the first column, fill the first have rows with <em>T</em>s, and the second half rows with <em>F</em>s</li>
<li>Divide the rows in half again. In the second column, fill the first quarter rows with <em>T</em>s, the second quarter with <em>F</em>s, and continue on, alternating every quarter.</li>
<li>Continue this process until the column for your last propositional variable has alternating <em>T</em>s and <em>F</em>s all the way down.</li>
</ul></li>
</ol>
	</section>
	
<section>
	<section>
<h1>Truth table for negation</h1>
<p>~p</p>
<ul>
<li class="fragment">Negation switches the truth value of the contained proposition.</li>
<li class="fragment">We call the contained proposition the <em>prejacent</em></li>
<li class="fragment">If the prejacent is true, then the negation is false, and if the prejacent is false, then the negation is true</li>
</ul></ul>

<table>
<thead>
<th style="text-align: center;">p</th>
<th style="text-align: center;">~p</th>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr class="odd">
<td style="text-align: center;">T</td>
<td style="text-align: center;">F</td>
</tr>
<tr class="even">
<td style="text-align: center;">F</td>
<td style="text-align: center;">T</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
<caption>Truth table for atomic propositions</caption>
</table>
	</section>	
	
	<section>
	<h2>Truth table for conjunction</h2>
	<p><em>p</em> &#x2219; <em>q</em></p>
	
	<ul>
	<li class="fragment">A conjunction is true just in case <em>both</em> of the propositions that make it up are true.</li>
	<li class="fragment">We call each of the propositions in a conjunction a <em>conjunct</em>.</li>
	<li class="fragment">Since there are two conjuncts, the truth table has 4 rows.</ul>
	
	<table>
<caption>Truth table for conjunction</caption>
<thead>
<th style="text-align: center;">p</th>
<th style="text-align: center;">q</th>
<th style="text-align: center;">p &#x2219; q</th>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr class="odd">
<td style="text-align: center;">T</td>
<td style="text-align: center;">T</td>
<td style="text-align: center;">T</td>
</tr>
<tr class="even">
<td style="text-align: center;">T</td>
<td style="text-align: center;">F</td>
<td style="text-align: center;">F</td>
</tr>
<tr class="odd">
<td style="text-align: center;">F</td>
<td style="text-align: center;">T</td>
<td style="text-align: center;">F</td>
</tr>
<tr class="even">
<td style="text-align: center;">F</td>
<td style="text-align: center;">F</td>
<td style="text-align: center;">F</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</section>
</section>

	<section>
	<h2>Truth table for disjunction</h2>
	<p><em>p</em> &#x2228; <em>q</em></p>
	
	<ul>
	<li class="fragment">A disjunction is true just in case <em>at least one</em> of the propositions that make it up are true.</li>
	<li class="fragment">We call each of the propositions in a disjunction a <em>disjunct</em>.</li>
	<li class="fragment">Since there are two disjuncts, the truth table has 4 rows.</ul>
	
	<table>
<caption>Truth table for disjunction</caption>
<thead>
<th style="text-align: center;">p</th>
<th style="text-align: center;">q</th>
<th style="text-align: center;">p &#x2228; q</th>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr class="odd">
<td style="text-align: center;">T</td>
<td style="text-align: center;">T</td>
<td style="text-align: center;">T</td>
</tr>
<tr class="even">
<td style="text-align: center;">T</td>
<td style="text-align: center;">F</td>
<td style="text-align: center;">T</td>
</tr>
<tr class="odd">
<td style="text-align: center;">F</td>
<td style="text-align: center;">T</td>
<td style="text-align: center;">T</td>
</tr>
<tr class="even">
<td style="text-align: center;">F</td>
<td style="text-align: center;">F</td>
<td style="text-align: center;">F</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</section>

	<section>
	<h2>Truth table for conditionals</h2>
	<p><em>p</em> &#x2283; <em>q</em></p>
	
	<ul>
	<li class="fragment">We call the first proposition in a conditional the <em>antecedent</em>, and the second proposition the <em>consequent</em>.</li>
	<li class="fragment">A conditional is true just in case <em>either</em> the antecedent is false, or the consequent is true.</li>
	
	<table>
<caption>Truth table for conditionals</caption>
<thead>
<th style="text-align: center;">p</th>
<th style="text-align: center;">q</th>
<th style="text-align: center;">p &#x2283; q</th>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr class="odd">
<td style="text-align: center;">T</td>
<td style="text-align: center;">T</td>
<td style="text-align: center;">T</td>
</tr>
<tr class="even">
<td style="text-align: center;">T</td>
<td style="text-align: center;">F</td>
<td style="text-align: center;">F</td>
</tr>
<tr class="odd">
<td style="text-align: center;">F</td>
<td style="text-align: center;">T</td>
<td style="text-align: center;">T</td>
</tr>
<tr class="even">
<td style="text-align: center;">F</td>
<td style="text-align: center;">F</td>
<td style="text-align: center;">T</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</section>

	<section>
	<h2>Truth table for biconditionals</h2>
	<p><em>p</em> &#x2261; <em>q</em></p>
	
	<ul>
	<li class="fragment">We call the first proposition in a conditional the <em>antecedent</em>, and the second proposition the <em>consequent</em>.</li>
	<li class="fragment">A biconditional is true just in case the antecedent and the consequent have <em>the same truth value</em>.</li>
	
	<table>
<caption>Truth table for biconditionals</caption>
<thead>
<th style="text-align: center;">p</th>
<th style="text-align: center;">q</th>
<th style="text-align: center;">p &#x2261; q</th>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr class="odd">
<td style="text-align: center;">T</td>
<td style="text-align: center;">T</td>
<td style="text-align: center;">T</td>
</tr>
<tr class="even">
<td style="text-align: center;">T</td>
<td style="text-align: center;">F</td>
<td style="text-align: center;">F</td>
</tr>
<tr class="odd">
<td style="text-align: center;">F</td>
<td style="text-align: center;">T</td>
<td style="text-align: center;">F</td>
</tr>
<tr class="even">
<td style="text-align: center;">F</td>
<td style="text-align: center;">F</td>
<td style="text-align: center;">T</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</section>
